, 
<geoCoordinate id="EE7950539245E961D7A1FE888D21FEA2" box="[957,1054,293,313]" degrees="21" direction="east" minutes="46" orientation="longitude" pageId="29" pageNumber="362" precision="15" seconds="30" value="21.775">21°46'30E</geoCoordinate>
, 
<date id="FFF310549245E961D48BFE91883FFECB" box="[151,256,316,336]" pageId="29" pageNumber="362" value="1997-03-27">27.III.1997</date>
, V. Assing (cAss, cWun).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF236949245E961D48BFECD884FFE28" blockId="29.[151,1059,351,435]" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">
D e s c r i p t i o n: 
<quantity id="4CB59B719245E961D59DFEF288C0FEEE" box="[385,511,351,373]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" metricValueMax="2.7" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="29" pageNumber="362" unit="mm" value="2.6" valueMax="2.7" valueMin="2.5">2.5-2.7 mm</quantity>
. Coloration: whole body reddish yellow, with the central part of tergite VI and the anterior half of tergite VII infuscated; legs yellow. Habitus as in 
<figureCitation id="13762A119245E961D53EFE308853FE28" box="[290,364,413,435]" captionStart="Figs 84-94" captionStartId="41.[151,191,1355,1375]" captionTargetBox="[151,1060,204,1313]" captionTargetId="figure-4@41.[151,1064,377,856]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="Figs 84-94: Oxypoda afimbriata sp.n. (84-90) and O. praecisa sp.n. (91-94). (84, 91) habitus; (85, 92) forebody; (86, 93) head in lateral view; (87, 94) antenna; (88-89) median lobe of aedagus in lateral and in ventral view; (90) apical lobe of paramere. Scale bars: 84, 91: 1.0 mm; 85, 92: 0.5 mm; 86-87, 93-94: 0.2 mm; 88-90: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5433249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5433249/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">Fig. 84</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF236949245E961D48BFE6E89EFFDE8" blockId="29.[151,1059,451,627]" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">
Head indistinctly transverse; puncturation dense, but very shallow and somewhat illdefined; microsculpture very shallow (
<figureCitation id="13762A119245E961D636FE4F8B47FE63" box="[554,632,482,504]" captionStart="Figs 84-94" captionStartId="41.[151,191,1355,1375]" captionTargetBox="[151,1060,204,1313]" captionTargetId="figure-4@41.[151,1064,377,856]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="Figs 84-94: Oxypoda afimbriata sp.n. (84-90) and O. praecisa sp.n. (91-94). (84, 91) habitus; (85, 92) forebody; (86, 93) head in lateral view; (87, 94) antenna; (88-89) median lobe of aedagus in lateral and in ventral view; (90) apical lobe of paramere. Scale bars: 84, 91: 1.0 mm; 85, 92: 0.5 mm; 86-87, 93-94: 0.2 mm; 88-90: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5433249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5433249/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">Fig. 85</figureCitation>
); eyes relatively small (
<figureCitation id="13762A119245E961D769FE4F8AFBFE63" box="[885,964,482,504]" captionStart="Figs 84-94" captionStartId="41.[151,191,1355,1375]" captionTargetBox="[151,1060,204,1313]" captionTargetId="figure-4@41.[151,1064,377,856]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="Figs 84-94: Oxypoda afimbriata sp.n. (84-90) and O. praecisa sp.n. (91-94). (84, 91) habitus; (85, 92) forebody; (86, 93) head in lateral view; (87, 94) antenna; (88-89) median lobe of aedagus in lateral and in ventral view; (90) apical lobe of paramere. Scale bars: 84, 91: 1.0 mm; 85, 92: 0.5 mm; 86-87, 93-94: 0.2 mm; 88-90: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5433249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5433249/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">Fig. 86</figureCitation>
), weakly projecting from lateral outline of head, distinctly shorter than postocular region in dorsal view. Antenna as in 
<figureCitation id="13762A119245E961D56EFDB28881FDAE" box="[370,446,543,565]" captionStart="Figs 84-94" captionStartId="41.[151,191,1355,1375]" captionTargetBox="[151,1060,204,1313]" captionTargetId="figure-4@41.[151,1064,377,856]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="Figs 84-94: Oxypoda afimbriata sp.n. (84-90) and O. praecisa sp.n. (91-94). (84, 91) habitus; (85, 92) forebody; (86, 93) head in lateral view; (87, 94) antenna; (88-89) median lobe of aedagus in lateral and in ventral view; (90) apical lobe of paramere. Scale bars: 84, 91: 1.0 mm; 85, 92: 0.5 mm; 86-87, 93-94: 0.2 mm; 88-90: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5433249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5433249/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">Fig. 87</figureCitation>
, antennomere X approximately 1.5 times as wide as long. Preapical joint of maxillary palpus somewhat dilated, slightly less than twice as long as wide.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF236949245E961D48BFD298B93FD4C" blockId="29.[151,1058,644,727]" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">
Pronotum 1.20-1.25 times as wide as head and 1.25-1.30 times as wide as long (
<figureCitation id="13762A119245E961D7D6FD298D29FD01" box="[970,1046,644,666]" captionStart="Figs 84-94" captionStartId="41.[151,191,1355,1375]" captionTargetBox="[151,1060,204,1313]" captionTargetId="figure-4@41.[151,1064,377,856]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="Figs 84-94: Oxypoda afimbriata sp.n. (84-90) and O. praecisa sp.n. (91-94). (84, 91) habitus; (85, 92) forebody; (86, 93) head in lateral view; (87, 94) antenna; (88-89) median lobe of aedagus in lateral and in ventral view; (90) apical lobe of paramere. Scale bars: 84, 91: 1.0 mm; 85, 92: 0.5 mm; 86-87, 93-94: 0.2 mm; 88-90: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5433249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5433249/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">Fig. 85</figureCitation>
); maximal width approximately in or a short distance anterior to middle; puncturation very dense, ill-defined, and asperate; surface almost matt.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF236949245E961D48BFD458896FC2D" blockId="29.[151,1059,744,950]" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">
Elytra approximately as wide as pronotum and at suture 0.85-0.90 times as long as pronotum (
<figureCitation id="13762A119245E961D4FAFCAB880DFC87" box="[230,306,774,796]" captionStart="Figs 84-94" captionStartId="41.[151,191,1355,1375]" captionTargetBox="[151,1060,204,1313]" captionTargetId="figure-4@41.[151,1064,377,856]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="Figs 84-94: Oxypoda afimbriata sp.n. (84-90) and O. praecisa sp.n. (91-94). (84, 91) habitus; (85, 92) forebody; (86, 93) head in lateral view; (87, 94) antenna; (88-89) median lobe of aedagus in lateral and in ventral view; (90) apical lobe of paramere. Scale bars: 84, 91: 1.0 mm; 85, 92: 0.5 mm; 86-87, 93-94: 0.2 mm; 88-90: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5433249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5433249/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">Fig. 85</figureCitation>
); surface somewhat flattened; puncturation coarser than that of pronotum, very dense, rasp-like, and ill-defined; microsculpture present; surface almost matt. Hind wings reduced, slightly projecting from under elytral hind margins when unfolded (
<figureCitation id="13762A119245E961D7E5FCE9898CFCE2" captionStart="Figs 84-94" captionStartId="41.[151,191,1355,1375]" captionTargetBox="[151,1060,204,1313]" captionTargetId="figure-4@41.[151,1064,377,856]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="Figs 84-94: Oxypoda afimbriata sp.n. (84-90) and O. praecisa sp.n. (91-94). (84, 91) habitus; (85, 92) forebody; (86, 93) head in lateral view; (87, 94) antenna; (88-89) median lobe of aedagus in lateral and in ventral view; (90) apical lobe of paramere. Scale bars: 84, 91: 1.0 mm; 85, 92: 0.5 mm; 86-87, 93-94: 0.2 mm; 88-90: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5433249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5433249/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">Fig. 85</figureCitation>
). Legs relatively short; metatarsomere I longer than the combined length of the two following metatarsomeres, approximately as long as the combined length of metatarsomeres II-IV or nearly so.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF236949245E961D48BFC6A88C6FBA2" blockId="29.[151,1058,967,1081]" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">
Abdomen approximately as wide as elytra, widest at segments V/VI, segments VII-VIII weakly tapering (
<figureCitation id="13762A119245E961D557FC4888A7FC60" box="[331,408,997,1019]" captionStart="Figs 84-94" captionStartId="41.[151,191,1355,1375]" captionTargetBox="[151,1060,204,1313]" captionTargetId="figure-4@41.[151,1064,377,856]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="Figs 84-94: Oxypoda afimbriata sp.n. (84-90) and O. praecisa sp.n. (91-94). (84, 91) habitus; (85, 92) forebody; (86, 93) head in lateral view; (87, 94) antenna; (88-89) median lobe of aedagus in lateral and in ventral view; (90) apical lobe of paramere. Scale bars: 84, 91: 1.0 mm; 85, 92: 0.5 mm; 86-87, 93-94: 0.2 mm; 88-90: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5433249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5433249/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">Fig. 84</figureCitation>
); puncturation fine and very dense on tergite III, gradually decreasing in density from tergites IV to VIII; microsculpture absent; posterior margin of tergite VII without palisade fringe.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF236949245E961D48BFBE78ABAFB27" blockId="29.[151,1059,1098,1212]" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">
3: posterior margin of sternite VIII obtusely angled in the middle (
<figureCitation id="13762A119245E961D75AFBE78AACFBFB" box="[838,915,1098,1120]" captionStart="Figs 71-83" captionStartId="40.[151,191,1412,1432]" captionTargetBox="[151,1061,205,1382]" captionTargetId="figure-4@40.[151,1064,434,913]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="Figs 71-83: Oxypoda brachyptera (STEPHENS) (71), O. lesbia ASSING (72-79), O. afimbriata sp.n. (80-82), and O. praecisa sp.n. (83). (71-74) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (72, 74: Timfristos; 73: Kato Olympos); (75) apical lobe of paramere; (77-79, 82-83) spermatheca (77: Timfristos; 78: Oros Giona; 79: Kato Olympos; 83: Panahaiko); (76, 81) ♀ sternite VIII; (80) 3 sternite VIII. Scale bars: 76, 80-81: 0.2 mm; 71-75, 77-79, 82-83: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5433247" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5433247/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">Fig. 80</figureCitation>
); median lobe of aedeagus shaped as in 
<figureCitation id="13762A119245E961D5A4FBC58B11FBE5" box="[440,558,1128,1150]" captionStart="Figs 84-94" captionStartId="41.[151,191,1355,1375]" captionTargetBox="[151,1060,204,1313]" captionTargetId="figure-4@41.[151,1064,377,856]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="Figs 84-94: Oxypoda afimbriata sp.n. (84-90) and O. praecisa sp.n. (91-94). (84, 91) habitus; (85, 92) forebody; (86, 93) head in lateral view; (87, 94) antenna; (88-89) median lobe of aedagus in lateral and in ventral view; (90) apical lobe of paramere. Scale bars: 84, 91: 1.0 mm; 85, 92: 0.5 mm; 86-87, 93-94: 0.2 mm; 88-90: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5433249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5433249/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">Figs 88-89</figureCitation>
, ventral process apically bifid; apical lobe of paramere of similar shape and chaetotaxy as in other species of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D179245E961D79FFB2A8D1DFB06" box="[899,1058,1159,1181]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Oxypoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brachyptera">
<emphasis id="B939EA869245E961D79FFB2A8D1DFB06" box="[899,1058,1159,1181]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">O. brachyptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, very long, with two long basal and two short apical setae (
<figureCitation id="13762A119245E961D731FB0B8A45FB27" box="[813,890,1190,1212]" captionStart="Figs 84-94" captionStartId="41.[151,191,1355,1375]" captionTargetBox="[151,1060,204,1313]" captionTargetId="figure-4@41.[151,1064,377,856]" captionTargetPageId="41" captionText="Figs 84-94: Oxypoda afimbriata sp.n. (84-90) and O. praecisa sp.n. (91-94). (84, 91) habitus; (85, 92) forebody; (86, 93) head in lateral view; (87, 94) antenna; (88-89) median lobe of aedagus in lateral and in ventral view; (90) apical lobe of paramere. Scale bars: 84, 91: 1.0 mm; 85, 92: 0.5 mm; 86-87, 93-94: 0.2 mm; 88-90: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5433249" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5433249/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">Fig. 90</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF236949245E961D48BFB7C8BB8FABD" blockId="29.[151,1058,1227,1318]" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">
<specimenCount id="9D4BFD1D9245E961D48BFB7C8993FB7D" box="[151,172,1233,1254]" pageId="29" pageNumber="362" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
: posterior margin of sternite VIII weakly convex (
<figureCitation id="13762A119245E961D6B1FB668BC7FB7A" box="[685,760,1227,1249]" captionStart="Figs 71-83" captionStartId="40.[151,191,1412,1432]" captionTargetBox="[151,1061,205,1382]" captionTargetId="figure-4@40.[151,1064,434,913]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="Figs 71-83: Oxypoda brachyptera (STEPHENS) (71), O. lesbia ASSING (72-79), O. afimbriata sp.n. (80-82), and O. praecisa sp.n. (83). (71-74) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (72, 74: Timfristos; 73: Kato Olympos); (75) apical lobe of paramere; (77-79, 82-83) spermatheca (77: Timfristos; 78: Oros Giona; 79: Kato Olympos; 83: Panahaiko); (76, 81) ♀ sternite VIII; (80) 3 sternite VIII. Scale bars: 76, 80-81: 0.2 mm; 71-75, 77-79, 82-83: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5433247" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5433247/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">Fig. 81</figureCitation>
); spermatheca as in 
<figureCitation id="13762A119245E961D7D9FB668877FA9C" captionStart="Figs 71-83" captionStartId="40.[151,191,1412,1432]" captionTargetBox="[151,1061,205,1382]" captionTargetId="figure-4@40.[151,1064,434,913]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="Figs 71-83: Oxypoda brachyptera (STEPHENS) (71), O. lesbia ASSING (72-79), O. afimbriata sp.n. (80-82), and O. praecisa sp.n. (83). (71-74) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (72, 74: Timfristos; 73: Kato Olympos); (75) apical lobe of paramere; (77-79, 82-83) spermatheca (77: Timfristos; 78: Oros Giona; 79: Kato Olympos; 83: Panahaiko); (76, 81) ♀ sternite VIII; (80) 3 sternite VIII. Scale bars: 76, 80-81: 0.2 mm; 71-75, 77-79, 82-83: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5433247" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5433247/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">Fig. 82. E t y m o l o g y</figureCitation>
: The name (Lat., adj.: not fimbriate) refers to the absence of a palisade fringe at the posterior margin of tergite VII.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF236949245E962D48BFA9A8837FEB3" blockId="29.[151,1059,1335,1572]" lastBlockId="30.[151,1059,212,296]" lastPageId="30" lastPageNumber="363" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">
C o m p a r a t i v e n o t e s: 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D179245E961D5E2FA9A8BEFFAD6" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2006" box="[510,720,1335,1357]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Oxypoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="afimbriata">
<emphasis id="B939EA869245E961D5E2FA9A8BEFFAD6" box="[510,720,1335,1357]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">Oxypoda afimbriata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
belongs to the 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D179245E961D79EFA9A8D1DFAD6" box="[898,1058,1335,1357]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Oxypoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brachyptera">
<emphasis id="B939EA869245E961D79EFA9A8D1DFAD6" box="[898,1058,1335,1357]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">O. brachyptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, as is suggested by the similar external characters and especially by the morphology of the median lobe of the aedeagus (general shape, internal structures, apically bifid ventral process), the shape and chaetotaxy of the apical lobe of the paramere, and by the morphology of the spermatheca. The new species is distinguished from the widespread 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D179245E961D48BFA7C880DFA7C" box="[151,306,1489,1511]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Oxypoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brachyptera">
<emphasis id="B939EA869245E961D48BFA7C880DFA7C" box="[151,306,1489,1511]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">O. brachyptera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D179245E961D57AFA7C88FDFA7C" authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2005" box="[358,450,1489,1511]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Oxypoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lesbia">
<emphasis id="B939EA869245E961D57AFA7C88FDFA7C" box="[358,450,1489,1511]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">O. lesbia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the paler coloration, which somewhat resembles that of some species of the subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D179245E961D5D7FA428B0EF99E" box="[459,561,1519,1541]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Oxypoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Deropoda">
<emphasis id="B939EA869245E961D5D7FA428B0EF99E" box="[459,561,1519,1541]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="362">Deropoda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, by the much coarser and more asperate puncturation of the pronotum and the elytra, by the absence of a palisade fringe at the posterior margin of tergite VII, by the shape of the median lobe of the aedeagus, and by the shape of the spermathecal duct, which is longer and more slender than in 
<taxonomicName id="4C4D4D179246E962D742FF5E8A83FE92" authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2005" box="[862,956,243,265]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Oxypoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="363" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lesbia">
<emphasis id="B939EA869246E962D742FF5E8A83FE92" box="[862,956,243,265]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="363">O. lesbia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<figureCitation id="13762A119246E962D7EBFF5E89C3FEB3" captionStart="Figs 71-83" captionStartId="40.[151,191,1412,1432]" captionTargetBox="[151,1061,205,1382]" captionTargetId="figure-4@40.[151,1064,434,913]" captionTargetPageId="40" captionText="Figs 71-83: Oxypoda brachyptera (STEPHENS) (71), O. lesbia ASSING (72-79), O. afimbriata sp.n. (80-82), and O. praecisa sp.n. (83). (71-74) median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (72, 74: Timfristos; 73: Kato Olympos); (75) apical lobe of paramere; (77-79, 82-83) spermatheca (77: Timfristos; 78: Oros Giona; 79: Kato Olympos; 83: Panahaiko); (76, 81) ♀ sternite VIII; (80) 3 sternite VIII. Scale bars: 76, 80-81: 0.2 mm; 71-75, 77-79, 82-83: 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5433247" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5433247/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="363">Figs 77-79, 82</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF236949246E962D48BFE94885BFE30" blockId="30.[151,1059,312,427]" pageId="30" pageNumber="363">
D i s t r i b u t i o n a n d b i o n o m i c s: The species is known only from the Erimanthos range in the northwestern 
<collectingRegion id="4989F8769246E962D638FEFA8B91FEF6" box="[548,686,343,365]" country="Greece" name="Peloponnisos" pageId="30" pageNumber="363">Pelopónnisos</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F35A76049246E962D6A6FEFA8A3DFEF6" box="[698,770,343,365]" name="Greece" pageId="30" pageNumber="363">Greece</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="13762A119246E962D70DFEFA8A68FEF6" box="[785,855,343,365]" captionStart="Map 3" captionStartId="28.[151,196,1071,1091]" captionTargetBox="[151,1065,375,1051]" captionTargetId="figure-76@28.[151,1065,375,1052]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="Map 3: Distribution of Oxypoda lesbia ASSING (filled circles), O. praecisa sp.n. (open circles), and O. afimbriata sp.n. (square) in Greece." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5433237" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5433237/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="363">Map 3</figureCitation>
). The reduced hind wings and palisade fringe at the posterior margin of tergite VII suggest that it has a restricted distribution.
</paragraph>
